# SQLite Database Standards

## Scope of This Rule

**This rule covers**: SQLite **implementation** - connection, setup, migrations, library usage.

**For schema design principles** (tables, indexes, queries, performance), see **Rule 23** (database-rules.mdc).

---

## Database Setup

### Library Choice
Use `expo-sqlite` for Expo projects or `react-native-sqlite-storage` for bare React Native.

### Database Location
```typescript
// Database file location
const DATABASE_NAME = 'your_app_name.db';  // Update with your app name
const DATABASE_VERSION = 1;
```

## Schema Management

### Migrations
```
src/infrastructure/database/
├── database-manager.ts      # Database connection and setup
├── migrations/
│   ├── index.ts             # Migration runner
│   ├── 001_initial_schema.ts
│   ├── 002_add_weight_history.ts
│   └── ...
└── schema/
    └── tables.ts            # Table definitions
```

### Migration Template
```typescript
// Example migration - replace with your app's entities
export const migration_001_initial_schema = {
  version: 1,
  up: async (db: SQLiteDatabase) => {
    await db.execAsync(`
      CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS users (
        id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
        name TEXT NOT NULL,
        email TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL,
        created_at INTEGER NOT NULL,
        updated_at INTEGER NOT NULL
      );
      
      CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS items (
        id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
        user_id TEXT NOT NULL,
        title TEXT NOT NULL,
        description TEXT,
        created_at INTEGER NOT NULL,
        FOREIGN KEY (user_id) REFERENCES users(id)
      );
      
      CREATE INDEX idx_items_user 
        ON items(user_id);
    `);
  },
  down: async (db: SQLiteDatabase) => {
    await db.execAsync(`
      DROP TABLE IF EXISTS items;
      DROP TABLE IF EXISTS users;
    `);
  }
};
```

## Data Access Patterns

### Repository Implementation
```typescript
// Example repository - replace with your domain entities
export class SQLiteUserRepository implements IUserRepository {
  constructor(private readonly db: SQLiteDatabase) {}

  async getById(id: string): Promise<User | null> {
    const result = await this.db.getFirstAsync<UserDTO>(
      'SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?',
      [id]
    );
    return result ? UserMapper.toDomain(result) : null;
  }

  async save(user: User): Promise<void> {
    const dto = UserMapper.toDTO(user);
    await this.db.runAsync(
      `INSERT OR REPLACE INTO users 
       (id, name, email, created_at, updated_at) 
       VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?)`,
      [dto.id, dto.name, dto.email, dto.created_at, dto.updated_at]
    );
  }
}
```

### DTO Models
```typescript
// Data Transfer Object - matches database schema
// Replace with your app's entities
interface UserDTO {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  email: string;
  created_at: number;  // Unix timestamp
  updated_at: number;  // Unix timestamp
}
```

## Best Practices

### Transactions
```typescript
// Use transactions for multiple related operations
async saveUserWithProfile(user: User, profile: Profile): Promise<void> {
  await this.db.withTransactionAsync(async () => {
    await this.userRepo.save(user);
    await this.profileRepo.save(profile);
  });
}
```

### Parameterized Queries
```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Parameterized query (SQL injection safe)
await db.runAsync('SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?', [id]);

// ❌ BAD: String interpolation (SQL injection risk)
await db.runAsync(`SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = '${id}'`);
```

### Timestamps
- Store as Unix timestamps (INTEGER)
- Convert to Date objects in mappers
- Use UTC for consistency

### IDs
- Use UUIDs as TEXT primary keys
- Generate with `uuid` package or `crypto.randomUUID()`

## Testing Database Code
```typescript
// Use in-memory database for tests
const testDb = await SQLite.openDatabaseAsync(':memory:');

beforeEach(async () => {
  await runMigrations(testDb);
});

afterEach(async () => {
  await testDb.closeAsync();
});
```
